{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|かぶと|alt=冑,甲}}
[[File:Antique_Japanese_(samurai)_hari_bachi_kabuto.jpg|thumb|250px|{{m|ja|兜|tr=kabuto}}: a traditional Japanese '''[[helmet]]'''.]]

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=かぶと|-}}.  Found in the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' of 720 {{CE}} with the reading ''kaputo''.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

Derivation currently {{unk|ja|sort=かぶと|nocap=1}}.

* A surface analysis might suggest a derivation from {{m|ja|被る|tr=kaburu||to wear something on the head}}.  However, that reading derives from older form ''kagafuru'' and does not appear until 850,<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref> some time after the first appearance of ''kabuto''.

* An alternative analysis might suggest a compound of {{compound|ja|sort=かぶと|頭|tr1=kabu|t1=head|pos1=''[[kun'yomi]]'' and native Japanese term|兜|tr2=to|t2=helmet|pos2=''[[on'yomi]]'' and borrowing from Chinese}}.  However, the “[[head]]” sense with the ''kabu'' reading does not appear until near the end of the {{w|Muromachi period}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

* Word-medial bilabial plosives usually underwent [[lenition]], shifting along the lines of {{IPAchar|/p/}} → {{IPAchar|/f/}} → {{IPAchar|/w/}}, then vanishing altogether except where the following vowel was {{IPAchar|/a/}}.  This lenition often did not happen at morpheme boundaries in compound words.  The persistence of the {{IPAchar|/b/}} in ''kabuto'' might thus suggest that this term was originally a compound of ''ka'' + ''puto''.  The ''ka'' element is uncertain, possibly the {{ja-r|か-}} intensifying prefix added to adjectives; {{cog|ojp|-}} ''puto'' would be the stem and root of modern {{m|ja|太い|tr=futoi||[[thick]]; [[fat]]; [[stout]]}}, possibly in reference to the protective strength provided by a helmet.  This ''puto'' would then have undergone {{ja-rendaku}} to become ''buto''.
: Compare the phonology of adjective {{m|ja|か細い|tr=kabosoi||very slender}}, composed of this ''ka-'' prefix and adjective {{m|ja|細い|tr=hosoi|pos=ancient ''pososi''}} and demonstrating a similar retention of the bilabial plosive and {{ja-rendaku}}.

